- 0 (read)
- 1 (write)
- 2 (open)
- 3 (close)
- 8 (lseek)
- 60 (exit)
- 74 (fsync)
- 82 (rename)
- 87 (unlink)

But I also need to handle the syscall6 function, which is a regular function in the binary that the VM will execute naturally. The syscall6 function eventually calls the `syscall` instruction with the appropriate registers set up.

Wait, I also need to handle the case where the syscall6 function is called with a0=1 (SYS_write). In this case, the function checks if arg1 < 2 (fd < 2), and if so, forces a write syscall. Otherwise, it passes through the syscall number.

But since the VM will execute the syscall6 function naturally, I don't need to handle this specially. The VM will just execute the instructions in the syscall6 function, which will set up the registers and call the `syscall` instruction.

